### Acid-base reactions of hydrated ions

It is important to take account of the water molecules in hydrated ions. At first sight, the formation of iron(III) hydroxide Fe(OH)\({}_{3}\)(s), when sodium hydroxide solution is added to a solution containing Fe\({}^{3+}\)(aq) ions, looks like a simple precipitation reaction:

\[\text{Fe}^{3+}\text{(aq)}+\text{3OH}^{-}\text{(aq)}\rightarrow\text{Fe(OH)}_{3} \text{(s)}\]

This suggests that the reaction is similar to the precipitation, for example, of barium sulfate when sulfate ions and Ba\({}^{2+}\) ions are mixed together:

\[\text{Ba}^{2+}\text{(aq)}+\text{SO}_{4}{}^{2}\text{(aq)}\rightarrow\text{BaSO }_{4}\text{(s)}\]

However, such a treatment ignores the role of the water molecules. The Fe(H\({}_{2}\)O)\({}_{6}\)\({}^{3+}\) ion acts as a weak acid, \(K_{\text{a}}\) = 10\({}^{-5}\) mol dm\({}^{-3}\), because it undergoes an acid-base reaction with water molecules:

\[\text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{6}\text{(aq)}+\text{H}_{2}\text{O(I)}\rightarrow[ \text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{5}\text{(OH)}]^{2+}\text{(aq)}+\text{H}_{3}\text{O} ^{+}\text{(aq)}\]

If the H\({}_{3}\)O\({}^{+}\)ions are removed by the addition of a strong base such as hydroxide ions, further acid-base reactions can take place:

\[\begin{array}{l}[\text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{5}\text{(OH)}]^{2+}\text{(aq)}+ \text{H}_{2}\text{O(I)}\rightarrow[\text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{4}\text{(OH)}_{ 2}]^{+}\text{(aq)}+\text{H}_{3}\text{O}^{+}\text{(aq)}\\ [\text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{4}\text{(OH)}_{2}]^{+}\text{(aq)}\rightarrow\text{Fe(OH)}_{3} \text{(s)}+\text{H}_{3}\text{O}^{+}\text{(aq)}+2\text{H}_{2}\text{O(I)}\end{array}\]

The overall reaction with hydroxide ions is:

\[\text{Fe(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{6}\text{(aq)}+\text{3OH}^{-}\text{(aq)}\rightarrow \text{Fe(OH)}_{3}\text{(s)}+\text{6H}_{2}\text{O(I)}\]

The net result is that the ion has been deprotonated by a series of acid-base reactions and water ligands have been released.

Source: Chemistry for Advanced Level, Peter Cann and Peter Hughes

### Effect of ligands on \(E^{0}\) values

Different ligands can affect the **relative stabilities of oxidation states** in transition elements.

Example: \[\text{[Co(H}_{2}\text{O)}_{6}]^{3+}+\text{e}^{-}\rightleftharpoons[\text{Co(H}_{2} \text{O)}_{6}]^{2+}\text{\qquad}E^{\odot}=+1.81\text{ V}\] \[\text{[Co(NH}_{3}\text{)}_{6}]^{3+}+\text{e}^{-}\rightleftharpoons[\text{Co(NH}_{3} \text{)}_{6}]^{2+}\text{\qquad}E^{\odot}=+0.11\text{ V}\]

Observe the difference in the \(E^{\odot}\) values (and thus the difference in the ease of reduction of Co(III) to Co(II)) when different ligands are bonded to the same metal ion.

Two deductions can be made from the \(E^{\odot}\) values:

1. [Co(H\({}_{2}\)O)\({}_{6}\)]\({}^{3+}\) is more easily reduced / a stronger oxidising agent than [Co(NH\({}_{3}\))\({}_{6}\)]\({}^{3+}\).
2. NH\({}_{3}\) ligand stabilises Co(III) more relative to Co(II). Hence, **Co(III)** is **less readily reduced to Co(II) when it is bonded to NH\({}_{3}\) ligands**.